<p><i>Climate Change 2007</i>, the <b>Fourth Assessment Report</b> (AR4) of the <a href="/wiki/United_Nations" title="United Nations">United Nations</a> <b>Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change</b> (<a href="/wiki/Intergovernmental_Panel_on_Climate_Change" title="Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change">IPCC</a>), is the fourth in a series of reports intended to assess scientific, technical and socio-economic information concerning <a href="/wiki/Climate_change" title="Climate change">climate change</a>, its potential effects, and options for adaptation and mitigation. The report is the largest and most detailed summary of the climate change situation ever undertaken, involving thousands of authors from dozens of countries, and states in its summary,</p>
<ul>
<li>"Warming of the climate system is unequivocal."</li>
<li>"Most of the observed increase in global average temperatures since the mid-20th century is very likely due to the observed increase in anthropogenic greenhouse gas concentrations."</li>
</ul>
<p>Skeptics have made a <a href="/wiki/Criticism_of_IPCC_AR4" title="Criticism of IPCC AR4">variety of criticisms</a> against the report.</p>
